Joins — the seven types.

Spark supports the full S-Q-L join family, plus two Spark-specific shapes, semi and anti. This is a table you should memorise, because the exam quotes it almost word for word.

Inner returns rows where the key matches on both sides. Left — also called left-outer — keeps all the left rows and fills nulls on the right where there's no match. Right is the mirror: all the right rows, nulls on the left. Full — full-outer, or just outer — keeps everything from both sides and nulls the missing side.

Then the two Spark-specific ones. Left-semi returns the left rows that have a match on the right — but, and this is the key detail, it brings back no columns from the right side at all. Left-anti is the opposite: the left rows that do not match anything on the right. And cross is the full Cartesian product, which is rarely the answer you actually want.

Now, the join condition itself has three API shapes. If the key column has the same name on both sides, you pass a plain string — on equals "customer-i-d". If the names differ, you pass a column expression comparing the two. And for a multi-key join, you pass a list of column names.

The exam favourite here is left-semi. Picture the question "give me the customers who have at least one transaction." A plain select would scan every matching row; left-semi short-circuits at the first match per key and returns only the left columns. And its mirror, left-anti, answers "which customers have no transactions" — that's your standard anti-join for finding orphan records.
